WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.817 --> 00:00:04.150
SAURABH MADAAN: Hello, everyone.

00:00:04.150 --> 00:00:05.233
My name is Saurabh Madaan.

00:00:05.233 --> 00:00:06.940
And I'm very happy
to welcome you

00:00:06.940 --> 00:00:10.150
all to the next talk in
our investing series.

00:00:10.150 --> 00:00:13.490
I couldn't be more pleased than
to have here in person none

00:00:13.490 --> 00:00:17.710
other than James Grant.

00:00:17.710 --> 00:00:22.440
Mr. Grant has a lot of
accolades and accomplishments

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:23.880
that I'm going to talk about.

00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:26.830
But just to give you a
little bit of a flavor,

00:00:26.830 --> 00:00:32.119
he has a fantastic personality
and a charm with one-liners.

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:35.480
He comes up with them magically.

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:40.840
So before this talk, we came
here to this room for the talk.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.680
He was telling me, he said,
I'll explain investing

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:46.740
to you in ones and tens.

00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:50.370
And he said,
brilliant investing is

00:00:50.370 --> 00:00:53.150
when everybody agrees with you.

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:56.720
And he paused for like five
seconds and said, later.

00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:04.930
And today is going
to share with us

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:10.280
a tale of what he calls
the forgotten depression.

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:14.140
The forgotten depression
tells of the slump of 1920

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:19.300
and '21, with high unemployment,
collapse in commodity prices,

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:24.070
upsurge in bankruptcies, and
a sharp break in stock prices.

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:26.850
Unlike the Great
Depression, the 1920 affair

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:30.920
was over in 18 months.

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:35.210
What do you think the
Federal Reserve did?

00:01:35.210 --> 00:01:39.186
How much did they lower
interest rates by?

00:01:39.186 --> 00:01:43.260
Well, the fact is they
actually raised interest rates.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:47.160
And this is puzzling, right?

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:50.210
What explains the brevity
of this depression,

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:53.860
considering the actions
of the policymakers?

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:58.300
And Jim is here
to help in person,

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:01.550
to help us unravel
and deconstruct

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:04.300
what really happened
behind the scenes.

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:08.979
So Mr. Grant, James Grant,
is the founder and editor

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:11.090
of Grant's Interest
Rate Observer,

00:02:11.090 --> 00:02:15.170
a twice monthly journal
of financial markets.

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:17.600
He is the author of
works of history.

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:21.120
Example-- "Money of the
Mind: Borrowing and Lending

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.840
in America from the
Civil War to Michael

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:26.910
Milken," and biographies.

00:02:26.910 --> 00:02:30.490
Another example, "John
Adams: Party of One."

00:02:30.490 --> 00:02:33.590
His journalism has appeared
in the "Wall Street Journal,"

00:02:33.590 --> 00:02:36.290
the "Claremont Review of
Books and Foreign Affairs."

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:39.200
His television appearances
include "60 Minutes,"

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:43.790
"Charlie Rose," and a 10-year
stint on the "Wall Street Week"

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:46.460
with Louis Rukeyser.

00:02:46.460 --> 00:02:49.570
So without any further
ado, ladies and gentlemen,

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:53.558
please join me in welcoming
the one and only James Grant.

00:02:53.558 --> 00:02:57.382
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:59.772 --> 00:03:01.520
JAMES GRANT: Well, I thank you.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:05.205
And I thank Google, and I
thank the worldwide television

00:03:05.205 --> 00:03:05.705
audience.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:15.108
I'm going to stop
displaying the merchandise.

00:03:15.108 --> 00:03:17.020
But thank you for the thought.

00:03:19.990 --> 00:03:23.360
May I begin by
inviting you to imagine

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:27.910
that we are removed in time
to the late 17th century.

00:03:27.910 --> 00:03:32.680
And it's about 1685.

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:35.290
And you are in a
London coffee house.

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:38.610
And you see two of
your acquaintances.

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:42.610
One is Sir Isaac Newton.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:44.460
And the other is
Sir William Petty.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:47.890
No Petty will turn out
to be one of the founders

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:48.745
of modern economics.

00:03:48.745 --> 00:03:50.950
And of course,
Newton's reputation

00:03:50.950 --> 00:03:53.380
preceded him even then.

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:54.630
Smart cookies, both of them.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:04:00.850
Each, as you knew, intuited,
was on the verge of something

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:03.425
wonderful in his
respected discipline.

00:04:06.050 --> 00:04:08.930
Imagine now that you, a
citizen of the 17th century,

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:14.290
are transported in time and
in life to the present day.

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:16.928
And you are informed the
physicists have recently

00:04:16.928 --> 00:04:18.094
discovered the God particle.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:25.190
Whereas the economists,
who in 2008 failed

00:04:25.190 --> 00:04:27.180
to predict the
biggest cyclical event

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:32.800
of their professional lives,
are debating the efficacy of 0%

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:33.300
rates.

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:35.150
Or is it negative percent rates?

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:39.100
Or is it something else?

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:42.420
Plainly, physics has made a
different kind of contribution

00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:45.910
to human society
than economics has.

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:50.130
So I stand before you in
a most unlikely setting

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:53.480
in which to propose the
thesis that in matters

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:58.360
of money and credit, the world
has gone not ahead, but rather

00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:00.160
behind.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:02.060
If there's any audience
institution that

00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:06.320
ought to be skeptical of a
claim that progress is not

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:10.530
inevitable and wondrous
and irrepressible,

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:15.510
it surely must this
splendid company.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.240
But nonetheless,
that is my thesis.

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:20.140
I submit to you the progress, at
least in the physical sciences,

00:05:20.140 --> 00:05:20.930
is cumulative.

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:24.100
We stand on the
shoulders of giants

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:25.260
in economics and finance.

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:26.590
Progress is rather cyclical.

00:05:29.477 --> 00:05:30.060
We go forward.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:30.670
We go back.

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:34.690
But we keep stepping
on the same rake.

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:38.185
And in the four hours given
to you today so generously

00:05:38.185 --> 00:05:42.115
by the company, I'm going
to try to persuade you

00:05:42.115 --> 00:05:45.210
that we are, in fact,
stepping on the rake of money.

00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:48.230
Now the curious
thing about money,

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:50.540
we spend a-- now
as you can tell,

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:53.360
I'm not an employee of Google.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:55.800
You might infer by the fact
I did not get the memorandum

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:58.270
about dress today.

00:05:58.270 --> 00:05:59.754
On Wall Street.

00:05:59.754 --> 00:06:01.170
And people in my
neck of the woods

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:06.130
spend their entire lives trying
to accumulate dollar bills.

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:08.840
But I warrant to you
that not a single one

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:12.970
of my dollar-- I was
going to say grubbing--

00:06:12.970 --> 00:06:14.870
my dollar-accumulating
Wall Street friends

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:17.310
has devoted more than a
few minutes in the course

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:21.460
of his or her career to thinking
about the nature of that piece

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:27.354
of paper that he or she has
invested so many heartbeats

00:06:27.354 --> 00:06:30.693
in accumulating.

00:06:30.693 --> 00:06:33.920
You know, a bond is a
promise to pay money.

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:35.420
You've heard about
bonds, of course.

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:36.128
Debt instruments.

00:06:36.128 --> 00:06:38.290
But what is money?

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:51.410
So Chicago Cubs fans-- and now
the world is full of them--

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:55.160
might be wondering
about life the last time

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:56.350
their team was this good.

00:06:56.350 --> 00:06:58.610
That was 1908.

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:02.530
Famously, the Cubs have been
unsuccessful since that time.

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:04.690
They won the World
Series in 1908.

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:07.670
And to send out
a marker in time,

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:10.800
I'm going to describe
the financial and credit

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:14.380
arrangements prevailing the
last time the Cubs won the World

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:16.720
Series with the present
day, which is respectively

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:20.310
the next time the Cubs are going
to go someplace besides home

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:22.100
in October.

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:23.760
And the year is 1908.

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:26.520
And here is the way the
world worked with respect

00:07:26.520 --> 00:07:27.720
to money and credit.

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:30.930
With regard to
money, the dollar was

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:36.380
defined as a weight
of something tangible.

00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:42.450
Gold, $20.67 got you an ounce.

00:07:42.450 --> 00:07:43.920
That was written into the law.

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.450
The dollar was
convertible into gold

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:48.790
at the option of the holder
of the paper currency.

00:07:51.610 --> 00:07:56.030
Such seemed to be the logic of
the constitutional stipulations

00:07:56.030 --> 00:07:58.770
about money,
Article 1, Section 8

00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:02.390
defined money-- talked
about coining it.

00:08:02.390 --> 00:08:05.610
And in that same
constitutional breath,

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:08.250
Congress was given not only
that right, but also the duty

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:09.750
to set weights and measures.

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:13.120
Money was a weight
and a measure.

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.530
Money is today something
very different.

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:19.250
It has become an instrument
of national policy.

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:27.090
As to credit in 1908, the
stockholders of a bank

00:08:27.090 --> 00:08:30.260
were responsible for
its solvency, which

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:34.770
meant if an institution
became impaired or insolvent,

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:36.330
the stockholders
got a capital call.

00:08:36.330 --> 00:08:40.350
That is, the courts
ordered them to fork over

00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:44.220
the unpaid in portion of
the par value pro rata.

00:08:44.220 --> 00:08:48.110
So if you were a
bank stock investor,

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:51.130
and your bank hit the
rocks, the sheriff

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:53.720
would come calling
if you didn't heed

00:08:53.720 --> 00:08:57.265
the first call from the court.

00:08:57.265 --> 00:08:58.390
Which seemed to make sense.

00:08:58.390 --> 00:09:00.654
After all, you, the
stockholder, got the dividends

00:09:00.654 --> 00:09:01.820
when things were going well.

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:06.460
Why shouldn't you be responsible
for the debts of the firm

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:08.760
when things were not going well?

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.110
That was then.

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:12.360
Individual responsibility
and credit and money

00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:15.930
defined as an objective weight
and an objective measure

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:17.280
in the law.

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:20.660
So fast forward to today.

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:25.540
With respect to banking,
despite or perhaps

00:09:25.540 --> 00:09:29.090
indeed a little bit because
of the Dodd-Frank legislation,

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:32.630
even more are the biggest
banks in the country

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:35.195
the responsibilities
of the taxpayers.

00:09:38.860 --> 00:09:45.030
Risk to a great degree
has been socialized.

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:48.240
Removed from the province of
individual responsibility.

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:50.880
As to money, what is it exactly?

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:51.950
Well it's not defined.

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:55.020
A dollar is what the mandarins
at the Federal Reserve,

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:59.130
and with the market in
concert with the central banks

00:09:59.130 --> 00:10:00.100
choose to make it.

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:07.130
Here is an
observation concerning

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:12.400
the nature of modern money,
central bank-issued money.

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:19.620
So since our sorrows
of 2008, the world

00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:23.980
central banks have issued in
the aggregate about $10 trillion

00:10:23.980 --> 00:10:27.605
worth of something called money.

00:10:27.605 --> 00:10:30.387
I mean, even a gold
bug such as myself

00:10:30.387 --> 00:10:32.470
would not disdain to pick
up a hundred dollar bill

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:36.760
if he saw it lying
on the sidewalk.

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:42.510
But note the effort required
to materialize $10 trillion

00:10:42.510 --> 00:10:44.520
in purchasing power.

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:47.720
The effort required
is no greater, no less

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:50.645
than that required to tap
in anything on YouTube.

00:10:53.290 --> 00:10:57.520
The cost of production
of money is zero.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:10:59.690
In times past, the
cost was substantial.

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:06.460
It required human labor
to mine gold and silver.

00:11:09.650 --> 00:11:11.370
So the cost of
production is negligible.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:14.910
The effort to recreate
these units of currency

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:18.150
is negligible.

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:26.290
And we know, I mean,
we somehow know it even

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:27.570
if we don't actually know it.

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:32.460
We're aware that the money
is increasingly pixels.

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:33.490
No weight.

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:35.980
No corporeal substance.

00:11:35.980 --> 00:11:39.800
It exists on the hard
drive or in the cloud.

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:41.480
We know that, accept it.

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:48.910
Here is a story about one of
the not insignificant holders

00:11:48.910 --> 00:11:55.500
of American common equity,
including Alphabet and Apple

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:59.600
and Exxon Mobil and
Facebook and the like.

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:01.810
The holder in question is
a Swiss National Bank--

00:12:01.810 --> 00:12:04.180
the Central Bank of
Switzerland-- the gnome's

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:06.420
own Federal Reserve.

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:10.680
And the Swiss National
Bank, like some sort

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:14.220
of New York hedge fund, files
a 13F form every quarter.

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:19.940
13F form with the SEC
enumerates the filers' holdings

00:12:19.940 --> 00:12:22.640
of common stock, give
them some stock by stock.

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:25.830
And the Swiss National
Bank's filing is voluminous.

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:30.690
And you look down, you see
all these individual names.

00:12:30.690 --> 00:12:33.110
Owns 100,000 shares
of this, 40,000 shares

00:12:33.110 --> 00:12:36.220
of that, a billion to--
where did the Swiss National

00:12:36.220 --> 00:12:38.380
Bank get the money to do this?

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:40.340
Why, it created it.

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:42.000
It manufactured it.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:43.130
It materialized it.

00:12:43.130 --> 00:12:46.600
It conjured Swiss
francs with which

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:49.680
to suppress the unwanted
appreciation of the Swiss franc

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:52.620
against the euro.

00:12:52.620 --> 00:12:54.570
So it accumulates
euros with francs

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:55.930
that it invents for the purpose.

00:12:55.930 --> 00:12:57.620
And with those euros,
it buys dollars.

00:12:57.620 --> 00:13:02.060
And with those dollars,
why, it buys your company.

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:04.800
Buy shares in some great
tech companies, not

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:06.400
so great industrial companies.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:07.960
All manner of companies.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:12.340
2,600 different names
in the 13F filing.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.750
Now there's nothing
really different.

00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:18.330
Common stocks versus bonds.

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:21.060
The World Central Bank have
bought like $10 trillion

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:22.670
worth of bonds.

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:27.940
But to me, the vivid
nature of present day money

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:32.826
conjuring, of materialization
of these units of digital scrip,

00:13:32.826 --> 00:13:35.270
these ever so much more
vivid when you think

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:37.200
about something for nothing.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:39.490
And ladies and
gentlemen, the purchase

00:13:39.490 --> 00:13:44.255
of actual interest in
productive American enterprise

00:13:44.255 --> 00:13:46.670
is something.

00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:50.210
And the currency with which
those shares are purchased

00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:56.150
is, in some sense, nothing.

00:13:56.150 --> 00:14:01.720
So this talk, as
you can see, has

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:06.080
taken the form of a
lamentation rather than

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:11.130
a really helpful investment talk
with CUSIP numbers and ticker

00:14:11.130 --> 00:14:14.370
symbols, and the like.

00:14:14.370 --> 00:14:17.980
But I wanted to
emphasize-- I hope

00:14:17.980 --> 00:14:23.040
not to the point of ennui--
but still to emphasize

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:29.480
my basic thesis, which is
that we are to a great degree

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:32.210
the unthinking prisoners in
a kind of hall of mirrors.

00:14:32.210 --> 00:14:35.680
We are living in the world
of the central banks.

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:40.330
And I only wish that more of
us would speak up and protest.

00:14:40.330 --> 00:14:41.330
Like, where is the exit?

00:14:41.330 --> 00:14:42.975
How do we get out of here?

00:14:42.975 --> 00:14:46.880
What was the movie in
which the protagonist

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:49.930
lived in the world of a TV set?

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:50.930
AUDIENCE: "Truman Show."

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:51.804
JAMES GRANT: Ah, yes.

00:14:51.804 --> 00:14:52.510
Right.

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:54.080
Well, that's our world in a way.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:55.430
We live in a hall of mirrors.

00:14:55.430 --> 00:14:57.630
And it's a very pleasurable
hall of mirrors insofar

00:14:57.630 --> 00:15:00.847
as asset prices keep
levitating, and the rich

00:15:00.847 --> 00:15:01.680
keep getting richer.

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:03.138
Nothing wrong with
that, I suppose,

00:15:03.138 --> 00:15:06.460
if one is a member
of that fraternity.

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:09.480
But it is a world of artifice.

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:15.540
Now I claim to you
in the early going

00:15:15.540 --> 00:15:18.660
that in this most improbable
setting of progress,

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:22.390
innovation, and to be
sure, of imagination,

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:25.940
that in the very important
realm of finance and credit,

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:29.230
we are not progressing,
but rather retrogressing?

00:15:29.230 --> 00:15:31.206
How is such a thing possible?

00:15:31.206 --> 00:15:33.390
Well, I invite you
to just to join

00:15:33.390 --> 00:15:38.480
with me in a kind of
intellectual or historical

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:38.980
sidebar.

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:44.460
The year is now 2012.

00:15:44.460 --> 00:15:47.140
And as I recall, there was
another presidential election.

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:50.800
I can't exactly recall the name
of the Republican candidate.

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:52.820
Something to do with
Romney, I think.

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:55.480
Any case, not
entirely successful.

00:15:55.480 --> 00:16:00.490
Before his political failure
became common knowledge,

00:16:00.490 --> 00:16:05.330
there was a great
commotion among Republicans

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:09.390
to task the imminent
Romney administration

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:11.450
with the duty of
forming a commission

00:16:11.450 --> 00:16:14.750
to study alternatives to present
day monetary arrangements.

00:16:14.750 --> 00:16:16.630
That is to say,
let's do something

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:18.894
about the Federal Reserve.

00:16:18.894 --> 00:16:20.310
This was called a
Gold Commission.

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:24.200
The idea was to pick out the
best aspects of monetary regime

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:27.380
of yesteryear, and
perhaps to find

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:30.981
a way out of our
delightful-- that

00:16:30.981 --> 00:16:32.980
is for the asset portion
holding the community--

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:34.620
our delightful prison.

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:36.440
Our money prison.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:40.090
And this little thought
bubble of a Gold Commission

00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:44.130
was met with polite
smiles and in some cases,

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:46.540
outright derision,
by the savants

00:16:46.540 --> 00:16:50.557
of the economics profession,
especially the academic world.

00:16:50.557 --> 00:16:53.140
And one of them-- I believe it
might have been Larry Summers--

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:55.420
as long as Republicans
were thinking about gold,

00:16:55.420 --> 00:16:57.460
they might as well
investigate the possibilities

00:16:57.460 --> 00:17:01.460
of the commission to
bring back witchcraft.

00:17:01.460 --> 00:17:07.720
Well, I thought that
was a little abroad.

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:10.099
And it set me thinking
about an essay

00:17:10.099 --> 00:17:13.410
by Hugh Trevor Roper
published some time ago.

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:14.670
There's a delightful essay.

00:17:14.670 --> 00:17:18.589
I commend it to everyone who
was in the business of improving

00:17:18.589 --> 00:17:20.839
the future and of seeing
progress in action.

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:23.136
Namely, everyone in this room.

00:17:23.136 --> 00:17:24.950
And it's called
the "European Witch

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:29.650
Craze of the 16th
and 17th Centuries."

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:32.900
And in it, the
author, Trevor Roper,

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:35.487
sends up a warning signal
against the common presumption

00:17:35.487 --> 00:17:37.570
that the history of thought
traces a straight line

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:40.280
from the darkness to the light.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:43.200
Far from it, as he shows
by setting in evidence

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:46.620
the outbreak of quote--
"dark passions and infallible

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:51.270
credulities amidst the
flowering of the Renaissance."

00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:53.130
"And the belief in
witches was not,"

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:55.540
Trevor Roper writes,
quote-- "as the prophets

00:17:55.540 --> 00:17:57.350
of progress might
suppose, a lingering,

00:17:57.350 --> 00:18:00.240
ancient superstition,
only waiting to dissolve.

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:02.340
It was a new explosive
force, constantly

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:06.870
and fearfully expanding
with the passage of time.

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:08.860
Credulity in high
places increased.

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:11.820
Its engines of expression
were made more terrible,

00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:13.610
more victims were
sacrificed to it.

00:18:13.610 --> 00:18:16.260
The years 1550 to
1600 were worse

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:18.270
than the years 1500 to 1550.

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:23.090
And the years 1600 to
1650, more terrible still.

00:18:23.090 --> 00:18:24.860
Nor was the craze
entirely separable

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:27.850
from the intellectual and
spiritual life of those years.

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:29.830
It was forwarded by
the cultivated Pope's,

00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:32.570
the Renaissance, by the
great Protestant reformers,

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:34.480
by the saints of the
Counter Reformation,

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:37.320
by the scholars,
lawyers, and churchmen.

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:40.210
If those two centuries
were an age of light,

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:42.930
we have to admit that,
in one respect, at least,

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:46.670
the dark age was
more civilized."

00:18:46.670 --> 00:18:49.040
So it is possible,
it is possible

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:51.800
for forward-thinking,
intelligent, and imaginative

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:54.260
people to be in the
thrall of something that's

00:18:54.260 --> 00:18:56.470
palpably false.

00:18:56.470 --> 00:18:59.850
Could that something
today be the doctrines

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:03.190
of our doctors of economics?

00:19:03.190 --> 00:19:04.580
I suggest to you that it is.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:13.120
I think two winters
ago, I live in New York.

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:20.610
And on a Friday in January,
the National Weather Service

00:19:20.610 --> 00:19:22.747
issued a forecast
for a blizzard.

00:19:22.747 --> 00:19:23.830
And not just any blizzard.

00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:26.890
This was to have
been the greatest

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:28.660
blizzard in the
history of New York

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:31.610
since the arrival of the Dutch.

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:32.290
It's OK by me.

00:19:32.290 --> 00:19:33.070
I love blizzards.

00:19:33.070 --> 00:19:34.850
And my wife and I
made preparations

00:19:34.850 --> 00:19:36.580
for this onslaught.

00:19:36.580 --> 00:19:38.660
And we got ourselves
a reservation

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:41.160
at a local restaurant with
a great picture window.

00:19:41.160 --> 00:19:43.630
And we arrived Monday, the
day of the forecast, storm

00:19:43.630 --> 00:19:48.520
Monday night, to await this
fabulous meteorological light

00:19:48.520 --> 00:19:49.040
show.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:55.370
And as we sat down to dinner
and had a drink and [INAUDIBLE],

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:57.900
we couldn't help but notice
as the evening wore on,

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:01.310
that it wasn't snowing.

00:20:01.310 --> 00:20:07.590
And it's a lot to
ask of scientists--

00:20:07.590 --> 00:20:10.770
they write all the time--
the storm did land but 50

00:20:10.770 --> 00:20:12.203
miles to the East.

00:20:12.203 --> 00:20:15.000
But I got to thinking about
the nature of a snowflake,

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:21.280
as beautiful as it is, I guess
I was gonna say, as unique.

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:22.010
It is unique.

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:27.900
What snowflakes don't
do is watch CNBC,

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:31.900
and having imbibed the
forecast, do their best

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:35.340
to confound it through
contrary bloody-minded action.

00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:38.110
That's what snowflakes don't do.

00:20:38.110 --> 00:20:40.782
But we humans are
exactly in that business.

00:20:40.782 --> 00:20:42.490
Sell us something
that's going to happen,

00:20:42.490 --> 00:20:44.900
well, we make preparations.

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:52.439
And in the preparation,
we destroy the forecast.

00:20:52.439 --> 00:20:54.480
It's not going to happen,
because we have already

00:20:54.480 --> 00:20:56.500
taken the action
that was predicted,

00:20:56.500 --> 00:20:58.380
and maybe some other
action, besides.

00:20:58.380 --> 00:21:03.180
Now this speaks-- the
nature of humanity

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:05.154
and the nature of
prophecy-- speaks directly

00:21:05.154 --> 00:21:06.070
to the business model.

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:08.180
The people who make
these trillion dollars

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:11.010
of weightless,
non-corporeal money.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:20.400
I'm going to a favor
you with a-- the

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:25.280
Federal Reserve has on its
payroll 700 Ph.D. economists.

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:27.510
700.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:32.380
I'm gonna say that
you need 701 or none.

00:21:32.380 --> 00:21:34.740
It's not working.

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:37.190
And to get a taste
of the formative

00:21:37.190 --> 00:21:39.470
intellects at the
Federal Reserve,

00:21:39.470 --> 00:21:41.710
I invite you to visit
any website that

00:21:41.710 --> 00:21:45.790
lists the scholarly
productions of the employees.

00:21:45.790 --> 00:21:47.920
Here's one.

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:51.100
Computing dynamic stochastic
general equilibrium bottles

00:21:51.100 --> 00:21:55.460
with recursive preferences
and stochastic volatility.

00:21:55.460 --> 00:21:57.740
Now if you say those
words separately and read

00:21:57.740 --> 00:22:05.420
them backwards, well, the
general dynamic stochastic

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:11.120
equilibria model was the model
in place in 2006 and 2007,

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:14.900
and indeed, in 2003, 4, and 5.

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:20.170
And notice that it did
not set up any knowledge

00:22:20.170 --> 00:22:23.971
within the Central Bank of
the oncoming events of 2008.

00:22:23.971 --> 00:22:24.470
None.

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:33.070
Now this is relevant,
because the people in charge

00:22:33.070 --> 00:22:34.790
are indeed in charge.

00:22:34.790 --> 00:22:37.930
They have power.

00:22:37.930 --> 00:22:40.310
In particular, they have a
power over this seemingly most

00:22:40.310 --> 00:22:43.990
pedestrian thing called
the rate of interest.

00:22:43.990 --> 00:22:46.160
I speak perhaps with a
little bit of edge on this.

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:48.330
My publication is called
"Grant's Interest Rate

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:49.129
Observer."

00:22:49.129 --> 00:22:50.170
What are we going to see?

00:22:50.170 --> 00:22:51.930
There's no more interest rates.

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:53.280
God, interest rates were great.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:58.470
I remember we had them in 1984.

00:22:58.470 --> 00:23:00.180
But we don't have
them much anymore.

00:23:00.180 --> 00:23:04.740
They are so small, one
can barely see them.

00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:08.900
And in that fact
lies a great deal

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:12.590
of what-- lies much
of what can explain

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:14.370
present-day financial affairs.

00:23:17.422 --> 00:23:22.120
You know, interest rates
are prices, critical prices.

00:23:22.120 --> 00:23:26.150
We use them to set
investment hurdle rates

00:23:26.150 --> 00:23:33.780
and to calibrate risk, and to
discount projected future cash

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:34.280
flows.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:36.529
They are probably the most
critical prices in finance.

00:23:36.529 --> 00:23:41.020
Yet they are under the thumb of
the central banks of the world.

00:23:43.670 --> 00:23:45.880
Self-awareness is not
the strongest suit

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:48.280
of our monetary mandarins.

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:52.952
Ben Bernanke-- who now
is working for PIMCO,

00:23:52.952 --> 00:23:54.910
is kind of a capital
introduction professional,

00:23:54.910 --> 00:23:59.119
he helps people invest in
bonds-- was, as you know,

00:23:59.119 --> 00:24:01.160
the Federal Reserve Chairman
before Janet Yellen.

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:03.790
And in the day when
he was in office,

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:08.010
he gave a series of talks
in the public interest at I

00:24:08.010 --> 00:24:10.180
think George
Washington University

00:24:10.180 --> 00:24:11.580
in the District of Columbia.

00:24:11.580 --> 00:24:16.030
And in one of these potted
talks about the modern history

00:24:16.030 --> 00:24:20.702
of American economics,
he said, 1971,

00:24:20.702 --> 00:24:22.760
that was the year in
which for the first time

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:25.387
in a non-wartime setting,
the federal government

00:24:25.387 --> 00:24:26.345
imposed price controls.

00:24:26.345 --> 00:24:27.685
A very bad thing.

00:24:27.685 --> 00:24:28.310
Terrible thing.

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:31.950
Because after all, he
said in so many words,

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.910
prices are the signals, the kind
of traffic signals of a market

00:24:34.910 --> 00:24:35.410
economy.

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:38.570
If you make them all red or
all green through federal fiat,

00:24:38.570 --> 00:24:41.590
why, the traffic piles
up the intersections.

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:44.580
And that's dangerous
and inefficient.

00:24:44.580 --> 00:24:46.060
Prices, he said
in so many words,

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:49.170
must be discovered,
not administered.

00:24:49.170 --> 00:24:52.680
This was the man who
went on to execute

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:56.162
quantitative easing and 0%
rates and negative-- well,

00:24:56.162 --> 00:24:57.870
now they're talking
about negative rates.

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:08.390
So I think that the critical
failure of the present regime

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:15.230
in money is the conceit
that it is better for us

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:17.460
that prices-- these
critical prices--

00:25:17.460 --> 00:25:20.410
be administrative,
rather than discovered.

00:25:24.950 --> 00:25:28.790
A long time ago in the annals of
this-- since I started talking.

00:25:28.790 --> 00:25:31.800
It seems like a long time.

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:35.520
To me, if not to you.

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:40.530
My host made kind
reference to this product.

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:43.990
And this book is a
history of the Depression

00:25:43.990 --> 00:25:46.120
that people generally
don't talk about.

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:50.110
It was the one that
seemingly, as the title

00:25:50.110 --> 00:25:53.120
says, with some journalistic
license, healed itself.

00:25:53.120 --> 00:25:54.790
The depression healed itself.

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:01.975
The outlines of the
troubles took this format

00:26:01.975 --> 00:26:06.360
in industrial production down
about 30% between 1920 and '21.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:07.897
From peak to trough.

00:26:07.897 --> 00:26:09.730
Unemployment certainly
in the double digits.

00:26:09.730 --> 00:26:13.880
It was not registered,
but was certainly severe.

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:15.880
Stock market almost
down by half commodity.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:19.530
Prices down by 40 odd percent.

00:26:19.530 --> 00:26:21.160
Corporate profits down 90%.

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.370
It was something.

00:26:23.370 --> 00:26:26.440
And the government met this
with a balanced budget,

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:31.250
and as you have heard, with
higher, not lower interest

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:31.750
rates.

00:26:31.750 --> 00:26:32.940
Which was perhaps a mistake.

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:35.580
But still what
proceeded to happen

00:26:35.580 --> 00:26:36.860
was that markets adjusted.

00:26:40.360 --> 00:26:43.040
And prices fell.

00:26:43.040 --> 00:26:44.220
Wages fell.

00:26:44.220 --> 00:26:47.780
And because wages could
fall, profit margins

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:52.200
were restored at lower
levels of selling prices.

00:26:52.200 --> 00:26:53.340
So prices came down.

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:54.800
Wages came down too.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:57.800
Equilibrium was restored at
lower levels of activity.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:01.866
And because things were cheap,
profit-seeking individuals

00:27:01.866 --> 00:27:02.740
sought opportunities.

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:04.925
The sent money here
for that very purpose.

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:09.720
The gold price was fixed.

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:12.360
But the cost of mining it fell.

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:14.500
And because the cost
of mining it fell,

00:27:14.500 --> 00:27:16.920
profit margins for
the miners increased.

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:20.260
And they proceeded to produce
more of what in a depression

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:23.000
the world needs more
of, which is money.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.150
So automatic forces, or
quasi-automatic forces

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:28.630
in the marketplace
proceeded to do

00:27:28.630 --> 00:27:32.830
what government action in this
particular long-running cycle--

00:27:32.830 --> 00:27:36.730
it has been long-running, has it
not-- have so far singly failed

00:27:36.730 --> 00:27:39.300
to do.

00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:47.110
So in summary, my
lamentation is not

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:51.430
about investing, which I
think is a great calling.

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:53.490
Nor is it about the
United States of America,

00:27:53.490 --> 00:27:57.320
which is a pretty
good place to live.

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:05.480
But rather it is the persistent
and-- after the passage

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:07.420
of so much time--
almost unnoticed

00:28:07.420 --> 00:28:11.390
substitution of the visible
hand for the much more

00:28:11.390 --> 00:28:13.940
effective invisible one that
Adam Smith talked about.

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:23.770
I hope I have not held out
the notion of a free market,

00:28:23.770 --> 00:28:27.910
and of a price discovery as
a new kind of garden of Eden.

00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:33.710
For it was certainly not in
the '20s, about which I wrote.

00:28:33.710 --> 00:28:38.840
This is, after all, humanity
we're talking about.

00:28:38.840 --> 00:28:41.890
If things were so easy,
we'd be a great deal richer.

00:28:41.890 --> 00:28:43.620
I hope, say in conclusion now.

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:49.470
You look around this
wonderful campus.

00:28:49.470 --> 00:28:52.060
You see the fantastic
things that you all

00:28:52.060 --> 00:28:54.505
have given to the world.

00:28:54.505 --> 00:28:56.420
The world has purchased,
quite properly.

00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:04.790
But you wonder where were
our forebears all this time?

00:29:04.790 --> 00:29:09.510
Let us imagine that
the year is 45 BC,

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:13.060
or wherever the year
was that Cleopatra died.

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:20.010
And one of her public-spirited,
altruistic handmaidens

00:29:20.010 --> 00:29:23.580
made a deposit of the
