during the Black Death.

00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:13.860
Somebody might have
made a withdrawal.

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:16.200
And if the Bank of
Perpetuity had in fact

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:18.497
been perpetual, unlikely,
given the nature of leveraged

00:30:18.497 --> 00:30:19.455
financial institutions.

00:30:19.455 --> 00:30:22.750
They're always toppling
over, aren't they?

00:30:22.750 --> 00:30:28.430
And unlikely, given
the very human animal

00:30:28.430 --> 00:30:30.910
himself or herself, [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:30.910 --> 00:30:33.540
In fact, we're not
that good with money.

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:35.150
But we can be better.

00:30:35.150 --> 00:30:37.375
And it seems to
me the way forward

00:30:37.375 --> 00:30:40.430
is that a a paradoxical
means of stepping

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:42.440
backward and reclaiming
the institutions that

00:30:42.440 --> 00:30:47.040
worked so well the last time
the Cubs won the World Series.

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:49.824
So, that's my speech.

00:30:49.824 --> 00:30:51.240
SAURABH MADAAN:
Thank you so much.

00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:55.048
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:58.840
We were having a
brief conversation

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:00.590
before the talk began.

00:31:00.590 --> 00:31:04.110
And you shared a couple
anecdotes, which I thought

00:31:04.110 --> 00:31:06.630
would be very interesting
for this audience.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:11.660
So let me start
with one, if I may.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:15.160
You guys got a shout out in
the movie, "The Big Short."

00:31:15.160 --> 00:31:20.290
And you were mentioning to
me that during those days,

00:31:20.290 --> 00:31:23.000
you got a big pile of
documents in the mail.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.710
And you had a chemical
engineer working with you.

00:31:26.710 --> 00:31:33.360
And you asked him, what did
you make out of this material?

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:37.520
And they said, I
didn't understand it.

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:38.690
And your reaction was--

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:39.790
JAMES GRANT: Yeah.

00:31:39.790 --> 00:31:41.671
We got a story.

00:31:41.671 --> 00:31:42.170
No.

00:31:42.170 --> 00:31:43.880
It didn't make any sense to us.

00:31:43.880 --> 00:31:46.320
His name is Dan Gertner.

00:31:46.320 --> 00:31:48.570
And a very smart guy.

00:31:48.570 --> 00:31:55.280
And as you said, a chemical
engineer from his earlier life.

00:31:55.280 --> 00:32:00.070
And by no means
intimidated by complexity.

00:32:00.070 --> 00:32:02.860
And these documents
run thousands of pages.

00:32:02.860 --> 00:32:05.410
Very complex.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:08.100
But knowing that we didn't know,
knowing there was something

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:12.340
wrong, set us on the road to
persistence, which is always

00:32:12.340 --> 00:32:16.600
a good road to be on, unless it
winds up at a dead end, which

00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:17.620
sometimes happens too.

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:20.490
But we persisted and looked
at more of these things.

00:32:20.490 --> 00:32:25.310
And came to see that there
was actually no there there.

00:32:25.310 --> 00:32:27.809
And one of the ways
in which we came

00:32:27.809 --> 00:32:29.600
to understand that
we're on the right track

00:32:29.600 --> 00:32:32.900
is the pushback and
the friction that we

00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:35.832
encountered on Wall Street
from the stories we wrote.

00:32:35.832 --> 00:32:37.540
SAURABH MADAAN: They
were hostile to you?

00:32:37.540 --> 00:32:41.145
JAMES GRANT: Well, they
were-- well, hostile-- yeah.

00:32:41.145 --> 00:32:41.780
They were.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:46.695
Well, if we had
been wrong, it would

00:32:46.695 --> 00:32:49.070
have been Gertner's fault.
But as it were, we were right.

00:32:49.070 --> 00:32:50.742
So.

00:32:50.742 --> 00:32:54.320
But once we were summoned
over to a friendly talking

00:32:54.320 --> 00:32:57.370
to at Standard &amp; Poor's-- the
rating agency who wanted us

00:32:57.370 --> 00:33:01.520
to understand as to
how very wrong we were,

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:05.537
and how unhelpful we were
being to the situation.

00:33:05.537 --> 00:33:07.120
And then we really
knew we were right.

00:33:11.510 --> 00:33:17.360
SAURABH MADAAN: So did
additional evidence come in

00:33:17.360 --> 00:33:20.090
and help you refine the theory?

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:23.450
Like, what are some signals?

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:27.500
And the reason I'm asking is, in
terms of a lot of your audience

00:33:27.500 --> 00:33:30.450
here and on the
video on YouTube is

00:33:30.450 --> 00:33:34.820
going to be people who are
engaged in investing, possibly.

00:33:34.820 --> 00:33:36.390
Like, is there some
sort of pattern

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:42.540
recognition that one can
employ to be cautious?

00:33:42.540 --> 00:33:45.400
JAMES GRANT: Well, it's a
wonderful question to which

00:33:45.400 --> 00:33:47.060
there really is no answer.

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:52.190
One sees recurring
patterns in finance.

00:33:56.910 --> 00:34:01.710
I think with respect
to the Federal Reserve,

00:34:01.710 --> 00:34:04.270
to the central banks,
to the nature of money,

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:07.100
to interest rates, I
think there is setting up

00:34:07.100 --> 00:34:13.489
one of the great dramatic
moments in finance.

00:34:13.489 --> 00:34:18.530
There are upwards of $9
trillion worth of securities

00:34:18.530 --> 00:34:20.630
in the world that yield
less than nothing.

00:34:20.630 --> 00:34:22.400
These are debt
instruments, promises

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:26.510
to pay money undefined.

00:34:26.510 --> 00:34:32.050
And you, the investor,
pay the issuer

00:34:32.050 --> 00:34:35.340
for the privilege of-- you
could say this as many times

00:34:35.340 --> 00:34:35.840
as you want.

00:34:35.840 --> 00:34:38.360
It still won't make any sense.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:44.174
And I think I have in my
very hand, I have-- yes I do.

00:34:44.174 --> 00:34:46.090
I have a quotation from
"The Financial Times,"

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:48.780
a very distinguished
London newspaper, that

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:50.840
distills the mindset
of the market

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:55.900
today with respect to
investing in fixed income.

00:34:55.900 --> 00:34:59.610
Quote-- this is from
April 15 edition.

00:34:59.610 --> 00:35:01.810
Quote-- "Some banks,
pension funds, and insurers

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:05.570
must buy safe government debt
irrespective of the price."

00:35:05.570 --> 00:35:07.290
Close quote.

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:12.800
Now is any investment
asset intrinsically safe?

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:15.320
Is it intrinsically anything?

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:21.875
I mean, let me invite you
to go back in time, 1984.

00:35:21.875 --> 00:35:22.880
1984.

00:35:22.880 --> 00:35:29.000
So interest rates spent the
years 1946 to 1981 going up.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:33.450
It went from 2 and 1/2% at
the low in the spring of 1946,

00:35:33.450 --> 00:35:38.150
to 15% in the fall of 1981.

00:35:38.150 --> 00:35:38.850
15%.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:43.960
You could have invested in 15%
30-year US Treasury securities

00:35:43.960 --> 00:35:46.180
non call for 25 years.

00:35:46.180 --> 00:35:48.390
Equity returns with
no equity risk.

00:35:48.390 --> 00:35:49.810
You know who wanted that?

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:50.470
About nobody.

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:53.490
Because they had had
35 years of experience

00:35:53.490 --> 00:35:56.040
with falling bond prices
and rising interest rates,

00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:57.370
meaning losses.

00:36:00.410 --> 00:36:04.919
So interest rates
began to come down.

00:36:04.919 --> 00:36:07.210
Paul Volcker was in at the
head of the Federal Reserve.

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:09.360
And it seems as if
he were making good

00:36:09.360 --> 00:36:12.950
on his vow to kill
inflation dead

00:36:12.950 --> 00:36:18.034
through the mighty, blunt-edged
instrument of tight money.

00:36:18.034 --> 00:36:20.200
It seems as if he were on
his way to achieving this.

00:36:20.200 --> 00:36:22.820
And then comes the
spring of 1984.

00:36:22.820 --> 00:36:24.225
And for whatever
set of reasons--

00:36:24.225 --> 00:36:26.100
and there are always
pretexts on Wall Street.

00:36:26.100 --> 00:36:28.680
You can always make a story
about why something happened.

00:36:28.680 --> 00:36:30.460
But what did happen
is that interest rates

00:36:30.460 --> 00:36:32.150
went back up again.

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:34.285
And for just a moment
in the spring of 1984,

00:36:34.285 --> 00:36:36.520
not so many years
ago, you could have

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:45.250
invested at 14% for 25 years
in US Treasury securities.

00:36:45.250 --> 00:36:48.250
That was what Wall Street
calls the Retest of the Lows.

00:36:48.250 --> 00:36:51.120
A return to the low F
price, the high F yield.

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:52.755
That was on offer
in the spring '94.

00:36:52.755 --> 00:36:54.470
And again, very few takers.

00:36:54.470 --> 00:36:55.250
I was there.

00:36:55.250 --> 00:36:57.325
And we chronicled this.

00:36:57.325 --> 00:36:58.200
You couldn't be sure.

00:36:58.200 --> 00:37:02.950
You thought-- nobody knew that
a new cycle in interest rates

00:37:02.950 --> 00:37:05.580
would last more than 30
years, which this one has.

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:09.740
1981 to date of very low rates.

00:37:09.740 --> 00:37:12.640
And now people can't
get enough of securities

00:37:12.640 --> 00:37:16.400
in which you pay them.

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:16.900
So yes.

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:18.150
We've got pattern recognition.

00:37:18.150 --> 00:37:18.760
Yeah.

00:37:18.760 --> 00:37:24.650
And one of the patterns that
recurs is extremes of behavior

00:37:24.650 --> 00:37:26.900
and perception that
you feel are almost

00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:29.450
supernatural in their error.

00:37:29.450 --> 00:37:31.300
You can't believe.

00:37:31.300 --> 00:37:37.720
People in 1979, '80,
'81, were watching

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:40.720
bond yields go up from 9%, 10%.

00:37:40.720 --> 00:37:43.700
When Volcker came
in, October 6, 1979,

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:45.660
he gives a talk, a
press conference.

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:47.000
It's a Saturday.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:48.750
Emergency meeting on Saturday.

00:37:48.750 --> 00:37:51.980
And he announces that owing
to the crisis of inflation

00:37:51.980 --> 00:37:55.090
and of the dollar, that
he, Volcker, personally

00:37:55.090 --> 00:37:58.340
is going to oversee
the tightening of money

00:37:58.340 --> 00:38:03.830
such that he is going to
ring inflation by its neck.

00:38:03.830 --> 00:38:06.960
Or words to that effect.

00:38:06.960 --> 00:38:10.760
So that was the
announcement of intent.

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:16.080
At that moment, long-dated
treasuries were yielding 9%.

00:38:16.080 --> 00:38:18.422
As I say, by the
time he demonstrated

00:38:18.422 --> 00:38:20.380
to the satisfaction of
the investment community

00:38:20.380 --> 00:38:25.060
that he was serious,
they went to 15%.

00:38:25.060 --> 00:38:29.850
That was the degree of
mistrust of the institution

00:38:29.850 --> 00:38:32.190
of central banking
in the early 1980s.

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:36.420
Compare and contrast
the present day.

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:39.600
The economists at the Fed,
to a man and to a woman,

00:38:39.600 --> 00:38:42.600
virtually, missed, as I
say, the biggest event

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:44.819
of their professional lives.

00:38:44.819 --> 00:38:46.360
Yet they have come
out of this crisis

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:51.060
with greater power, greater
regulatory power, greater power

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:53.100
over interest rates.

00:38:53.100 --> 00:38:56.675
They have been the
instruments of the levitation

00:38:56.675 --> 00:38:58.477
of financial assets
through their talk

00:38:58.477 --> 00:38:59.560
and through their actions.

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:01.990
Stock prices have
gone up and up.

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:04.040
Cap rates on real estate
come down and down.

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:06.460
Interest rates down and down.

00:39:06.460 --> 00:39:09.610
The world of assets
thanks them profusely.

00:39:13.870 --> 00:39:18.580
But it's a truism that the
future promises lower returns

00:39:18.580 --> 00:39:20.200
the higher the price
in the present.

00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:26.580
It's a truism that is hard to
act upon if you're an investor.

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:28.861
God, it feels good
when it's going up.

00:39:28.861 --> 00:39:31.360
SAURABH MADAAN: Charlie Munger
says something that cannot go

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:33.130
on forever has to
come to an end.

00:39:33.130 --> 00:39:34.790
JAMES GRANT: What does he mean?

00:39:34.790 --> 00:39:36.350
Well, that is entirely true.

00:39:36.350 --> 00:39:39.080
But I'm here to tell you--
I think Charlie's got

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:39.910
a few years on me.

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:46.220
But I've been in situations,
and have been wrong enough

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:49.580
on some things that it seems
if things can't go on forever,

00:39:49.580 --> 00:39:50.485
can and do.

00:39:53.550 --> 00:39:55.500
SAURABH MADAAN: So
you've powerfully

00:39:55.500 --> 00:40:00.180
made the point of the so-called
invisible hand becoming

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:01.050
very visible.

00:40:01.050 --> 00:40:04.300
And you also refer to one
of the previous presidential

00:40:04.300 --> 00:40:07.020
campaigns.

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:08.630
What's the solution?

00:40:08.630 --> 00:40:11.500
Some say break up the big banks.

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:14.090
Others have other
solutions proposed.

00:40:14.090 --> 00:40:17.760
What do you think
is the way out?

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:19.750
JAMES GRANT: I think
constructive retrogression

00:40:19.750 --> 00:40:21.110
in our institutions.

00:40:21.110 --> 00:40:23.370
What I would like to see
is, first and foremost,

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:28.210
individual responsibility
being restored to Wall Street.

00:40:28.210 --> 00:40:30.750
There's one
financial institution

00:40:30.750 --> 00:40:33.370
in New York City that did not
take money from the Treasury,

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:36.750
took no TARP money, took
no bailout of any kind,

00:40:36.750 --> 00:40:39.370
and was virtually
invisible in 2008.

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:41.300
That was Brown
Brothers Harriman,

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:44.812
which was founded about
the time that Citibank was.

00:40:44.812 --> 00:40:46.505
My brother has a
general partnership

00:40:46.505 --> 00:40:49.020
in the organization, meaning
that the general partners are

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:51.676
themselves personally
responsible

00:40:51.676 --> 00:40:54.870
in a pro rata fashion for
the debts of the firm.

00:40:54.870 --> 00:40:57.680
Means not just that
their stock goes to zero,

00:40:57.680 --> 00:41:00.930
but they lose their Matisse,
their golden retriever,

00:41:00.930 --> 00:41:01.930
their house, everything.

00:41:01.930 --> 00:41:03.721
SAURABH MADAAN: They
have skin in the game.

00:41:03.721 --> 00:41:04.435
More than that.

00:41:04.435 --> 00:41:05.185
JAMES GRANT: Yeah.

00:41:05.185 --> 00:41:08.320
So it would be nice,
to my mind, to go back

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.800
to stockholders' liability.

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:12.830
But without being
punitive, one should

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:15.640
insist the people who
enjoy the upside ought

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:18.972
to be personally responsible, in
a leveraged financial setting,

00:41:18.972 --> 00:41:19.680
for the downside.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:23.170
The downside not just affects
them, but affects all of us.

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:25.050
So number one I
think, is to get away

00:41:25.050 --> 00:41:28.370
from socialized risk,
which I think is

00:41:28.370 --> 00:41:29.700
corrupting to the Republicans.

00:41:29.700 --> 00:41:31.950
I mean, it's
corrupting to finance.

00:41:31.950 --> 00:41:35.075
And then I think we have to get
away from the Ph.D. standard

00:41:35.075 --> 00:41:41.450
of monetary management, the
discretionary rule by people,

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:47.056
who as well-intended and as
well-credentialed as they are,

00:41:47.056 --> 00:41:49.582
are the practitioners
of a pseudo science.

00:41:49.582 --> 00:41:51.790
I mean, they say for instance,
they say for instance,

00:41:51.790 --> 00:41:53.750
the prices must go up 2% a year.

00:41:53.750 --> 00:41:56.860
That's the verdict of the
people who run monetary?

00:41:56.860 --> 00:41:57.546
Why?

00:41:57.546 --> 00:41:58.045
Why?

00:42:00.555 --> 00:42:01.130
Who says?

00:42:01.130 --> 00:42:02.480
Oh, they say.

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:04.030
But they don't explain.

00:42:04.030 --> 00:42:07.990
Is it just not possible that
by creating the extra credit

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:11.560
with which to try to force
prices in general higher,

00:42:11.560 --> 00:42:14.500
they create an
increment of credit

00:42:14.500 --> 00:42:18.810
that does great damage to the
structure of things in finance

00:42:18.810 --> 00:42:19.730
and in the real world.

00:42:19.730 --> 00:42:21.480
I mean, is it possible
that by doing this,

00:42:21.480 --> 00:42:23.210
they create bubbles
in real estate?

00:42:23.210 --> 00:42:25.760
In San Francisco
and in New York,

00:42:25.760 --> 00:42:30.090
real estate values are back
to levels from which they

00:42:30.090 --> 00:42:33.800
plummeted in 2006 and '07.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:38.280
So is this really
the way forward?

00:42:38.280 --> 00:42:39.980
This command and control regime.

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:45.141
You know, people tax the
proponents of new gold

00:42:45.141 --> 00:42:45.640
standard.

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:49.050
They tax them with,
it is an anachronism.

00:42:49.050 --> 00:42:52.110
Well, it does sound
as if it were.

00:42:52.110 --> 00:42:54.800
Why not bring back the
cutthroat rays of the sexton?

00:42:57.340 --> 00:43:00.870
Except there is a rather
subtle distinction

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:07.200
between things and methods,
as in methods and money.

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:11.970
the gold standard is about
a defined monetary unit

00:43:11.970 --> 00:43:13.500
that is a weight and a measure.

00:43:17.050 --> 00:43:20.960
And around that defined
weight and a measure,

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:25.800
people, through collaborative
means and markets,

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:28.460
through the social
media of markets,

00:43:28.460 --> 00:43:29.990
work out their own salvation.

00:43:29.990 --> 00:43:32.710
Now that sounds kind
of contemporary, right?

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:35.380
And if you casted the
present-day arrangements

00:43:35.380 --> 00:43:38.320
as command and
control, one thinks

00:43:38.320 --> 00:43:41.000
not of the enlightened
21st century,

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.550
but rather of say, Poland
in 1957, or something.

00:43:43.550 --> 00:43:44.050
Right?

00:43:44.050 --> 00:43:46.180
That's command and control.

00:43:46.180 --> 00:43:47.970
So I would say the
anachronism is really

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:51.030
on the part of those
who would defend rule

00:43:51.030 --> 00:43:56.075
by these-- I think they are
intellectual pretenders.

00:43:56.075 --> 00:43:59.000
And I think it's high time
that smart people began

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:04.100
to look into the science of
economics and say, or what?

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:07.560
What are we talking about?

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:15.500
