JAMES GRANT: Yeah.

00:47:08.862 --> 00:47:10.570
AUDIENCE: Thank you,
Mr. Grant for coming

00:47:10.570 --> 00:47:12.320
to speak to us today.

00:47:12.320 --> 00:47:17.470
So a few days ago, maybe a
couple days ago, Donald Trump

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:23.280
talked about essentially
defaulting on

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:24.757
like US government debt.

00:47:24.757 --> 00:47:27.090
And I was kind of surprised
that the markets didn't seem

00:47:27.090 --> 00:47:31.180
to react at all to that at all.

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:35.470
Do you think that as we get
closer to a possible Trump

00:47:35.470 --> 00:47:39.550
presidency, that this
might actually sort

00:47:39.550 --> 00:47:40.952
of slay one of the sacred cows?

00:47:40.952 --> 00:47:43.160
JAMES GRANT: Well, Donald
Trump speaks with authority

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:44.548
in the matter of default.

00:47:44.548 --> 00:47:47.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.645
Dozens of companies,
of course, hundreds

00:47:49.645 --> 00:47:53.470
have defaulted once
in modern times.

00:47:53.470 --> 00:47:55.990
Many fewer have defaulted twice.

00:47:55.990 --> 00:47:58.760
Many fewer still,
three and four times.

00:47:58.760 --> 00:48:01.700
Trump's Resort and
Casino in Atlantic City

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:05.260
holds the indoor record for
having defaulted five times.

00:48:05.260 --> 00:48:08.890
So this man speaks with
authority on the matter.

00:48:08.890 --> 00:48:13.280
Now by way of
historical preface,

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:14.680
the United States has defaulted.

00:48:14.680 --> 00:48:18.470
We defaulted on promise
to pay our debts

00:48:18.470 --> 00:48:21.070
in gold in 1933 and '34.

00:48:21.070 --> 00:48:24.840
That was known in the city of
London as the American Default.

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:27.800
And again in 1971,
when Nixon said

00:48:27.800 --> 00:48:30.880
that no more would be honor
promises to redeem dollars

00:48:30.880 --> 00:48:32.820
at $35 to the ounce of gold.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:35.340
So that was default number two.

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:42.840
And there is a default built
into the monetary method

00:48:42.840 --> 00:48:44.660
of trying to achieve
2% inflation per year

00:48:44.660 --> 00:48:46.590
over the course
of a 30-year bond.

00:48:46.590 --> 00:48:50.762
Of course, 2% loss of purchasing
power every year adds up.

00:48:50.762 --> 00:48:52.470
And you're not looking
at much in the way

00:48:52.470 --> 00:48:54.240
of return in purchasing power.

00:48:54.240 --> 00:48:57.200
So the default is
a defined term.

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:00.410
Now, I think apropo of Donald
Trump's remarks on Monday, sir,

00:49:00.410 --> 00:49:01.470
you have to keep up.

00:49:01.470 --> 00:49:03.011
He recanted that on
Monday afternoon.

00:49:05.380 --> 00:49:09.240
Every day's a new adventure
in his policy making.

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:12.390
But he's all about negotiating.

00:49:12.390 --> 00:49:13.410
So I don't know.

00:49:13.410 --> 00:49:20.760
I mean the way to think about
the American public debt,

00:49:20.760 --> 00:49:23.410
I suggest you visit the
Cato Institute website.

00:49:23.410 --> 00:49:27.340
There's a free analysis
available by a very good

00:49:27.340 --> 00:49:28.930
thinker named Jeffrey Miron.

00:49:28.930 --> 00:49:30.760
M-I-R-O-N.

00:49:30.760 --> 00:49:33.840
And in this analysis,
he says, let's

00:49:33.840 --> 00:49:38.760
take the present value of
American government promises

00:49:38.760 --> 00:49:41.120
to pay, that is, the
policies in place

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:44.800
now, especially medical
care, social security.

00:49:44.800 --> 00:49:49.430
Let us assume those go forward
as now budgeted for 75 years.

00:49:49.430 --> 00:49:52.840
And let us compare the
present value of expected tax

00:49:52.840 --> 00:49:54.820
revenues using
assumptions, which

00:49:54.820 --> 00:49:57.590
of course, might be errant.

00:49:57.590 --> 00:50:00.950
And compare those to the present
value of expected outlays

00:50:00.950 --> 00:50:03.035
and the present value
of expected income

00:50:03.035 --> 00:50:04.410
for the government.

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:10.410
And the difference in the
present value is $120 trillion.

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:12.491
That's the whole.

00:50:12.491 --> 00:50:13.740
So that's what they call them.

00:50:13.740 --> 00:50:17.050
The trade unsustainable,
unless something is done.

00:50:17.050 --> 00:50:19.610
Now Donald Trump wants
more medical care.

00:50:19.610 --> 00:50:22.660
He wants-- to make America
great, you have to be healthy.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:24.410
So he wants more of this stuff.

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:29.090
And I dare say that his likely
democratic sparring partner

00:50:29.090 --> 00:50:30.360
is going to want more as well.

00:50:30.360 --> 00:50:33.620
So the question to
me about default

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:38.700
is rather more nuanced than
the Trump Resort and Casino

00:50:38.700 --> 00:50:41.590
simply not paying and
getting really clever lawyers

00:50:41.590 --> 00:50:43.990
to rewrite the covenants.

00:50:43.990 --> 00:50:47.412
But I think that some
adjustment in our debt burden

00:50:47.412 --> 00:50:48.120
is in our future.

00:50:48.120 --> 00:50:51.760
Either through-- I don't
know-- through something.

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:54.410
Perhaps through inflation, or
perhaps through negotiation.

00:50:54.410 --> 00:50:57.780
AUDIENCE: How do you feel
about an audit of the Fed?

00:50:57.780 --> 00:51:01.180
And if that were to happen,
what are your hopes or fears

00:51:01.180 --> 00:51:03.970
about what might be discovered
and what action might

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:06.430
be taken as a result of that?

00:51:06.430 --> 00:51:13.570
JAMES GRANT: I think the audit
ought to look at not only

00:51:13.570 --> 00:51:15.930
the balance sheet and the
finances, which I guess

00:51:15.930 --> 00:51:18.070
are kind of OK.

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:20.160
Although awfully big.

00:51:20.160 --> 00:51:22.110
Trillions upon trillions.

00:51:22.110 --> 00:51:30.200
But I think an audit ought
to go into the assumptions

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:34.344
and the analyses that
inform the Fed's actions.

00:51:34.344 --> 00:51:36.760
I think the more sunlight on
this institution, the better.

00:51:36.760 --> 00:51:42.610
I mean, the Fed ought to be
regarded as a vast government

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:44.570
monopoly.

00:51:44.570 --> 00:51:48.200
And what every monopoly
needs is competition.

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:50.200
So as much I'd like to
see an audit for the Fed,

00:51:50.200 --> 00:51:55.360
I would also like to see a
simple change in the tax system

00:51:55.360 --> 00:51:59.260
such that silver and gold would
not be taxed as a collectible,

00:51:59.260 --> 00:52:03.380
but rather we treat it as money
in the tax system, whereby

00:52:03.380 --> 00:52:07.910
gold could compete in the open
market for monetary allegiance.

00:52:07.910 --> 00:52:11.720
There's a company called
Gold Money, which is

00:52:11.720 --> 00:52:13.990
kind of like a bitcoin thing.

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:16.902
And it's a very small caliber
enterprise at the moment.

00:52:16.902 --> 00:52:18.110
But why not give it a chance?

00:52:18.110 --> 00:52:19.318
Let's see what people choose.

00:52:21.840 --> 00:52:22.550
So yes.

00:52:22.550 --> 00:52:27.195
The Fed, more sunlight the
better, and competition please.

00:52:27.195 --> 00:52:27.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:31.254
I know a lot of the
liberal intelligentsia,

00:52:31.254 --> 00:52:33.420
like Lawrence Summers, make
fun of the gold standard

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:35.820
and compare it to witchcraft.

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:42.160
And I'm curious how in practice
would you bring it back?

00:52:42.160 --> 00:52:44.260
What would be the
steps you would take?

00:52:44.260 --> 00:52:46.966
What would be the
outcomes, et cetera?

00:52:46.966 --> 00:52:48.340
JAMES GRANT: It's
a big question.

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:50.140
And I won't tax you
and the audience

00:52:50.140 --> 00:52:56.050
with details which
I'm not sure I can

00:52:56.050 --> 00:52:57.660
do a very good job explaining.

00:52:57.660 --> 00:53:03.070
But I think the essence would
be to define money as a material

00:53:03.070 --> 00:53:07.280
object, as a weight
and a measure,

00:53:07.280 --> 00:53:11.490
and to fix currency
values internationally.

00:53:11.490 --> 00:53:14.720
So you have to coordinate
among the leading countries

00:53:14.720 --> 00:53:17.910
and to restore fixed exchange
rates, which after all, were

00:53:17.910 --> 00:53:20.300
they regime in place
from the founding--

00:53:20.300 --> 00:53:22.180
really in this country,
the founding to 1971.

00:53:25.270 --> 00:53:29.030
Our experience with
pure fiat currency

00:53:29.030 --> 00:53:33.390
and with floating exchange
rates dates only really to 1971.

00:53:33.390 --> 00:53:36.960
So it's a very small experiment
in the long-running history

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:37.460
of money.

00:53:40.490 --> 00:53:42.700
I think a lot of
people are hung up

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:46.549
on the evident anachronism
of people walking around

00:53:46.549 --> 00:53:48.090
with a bunch of gold
in their pocket.

00:53:48.090 --> 00:53:50.570
And they wouldn't.

00:53:50.570 --> 00:53:52.970
Even in the 19th
century, they didn't.

00:53:52.970 --> 00:53:56.010
Bank notes where
portable, light.

00:53:56.010 --> 00:54:01.010
There was a panic in the
city of London in 1825.

00:54:01.010 --> 00:54:08.950
And the authorities, to
intervene and to quell this,

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:10.590
gave the Bank of
England permission

00:54:10.590 --> 00:54:12.070
to issue one pound notes.

00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:13.660
Previously they
could not do that.

00:54:13.660 --> 00:54:15.720
The only sovereign
gold coins, one pound,

00:54:15.720 --> 00:54:19.090
were each little tiny things.

00:54:19.090 --> 00:54:21.160
And people were glad for it.

00:54:21.160 --> 00:54:23.220
And they didn't
really-- what gold does

00:54:23.220 --> 00:54:26.145
is to serve to anchor value.

00:54:26.145 --> 00:54:30.410
And in this day and
age, when your phone

00:54:30.410 --> 00:54:32.510
is your bank and your
brokerage account,

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:39.880
and so many other things,
you could deal in gold

00:54:39.880 --> 00:54:40.800
electronically.

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:43.070
It's infinitely
divisible in weight.

00:54:43.070 --> 00:54:45.610
It's one of its many
monetary features.

00:54:45.610 --> 00:54:50.490
So I think what
gold would do would

00:54:50.490 --> 00:54:53.115
be-- what the effect
would be would

00:54:53.115 --> 00:54:59.030
be to create an objective value
around which prices would move,

00:54:59.030 --> 00:55:02.400
rather than now changing
the value of money

00:55:02.400 --> 00:55:05.570
so that prices and wages
don't have to move.

00:55:05.570 --> 00:55:11.590
Now that would be a change that
the American people would have

00:55:11.590 --> 00:55:13.320
to choose to accept or not.

00:55:13.320 --> 00:55:16.450
It's rather a big change.

00:55:16.450 --> 00:55:22.110
But we have borne seven or eight
years of this sleepwalking, 1

00:55:22.110 --> 00:55:23.280
and 1/2% growth.

00:55:23.280 --> 00:55:24.510
There's something wrong.

00:55:24.510 --> 00:55:27.070
And I think in the
course of auditing

00:55:27.070 --> 00:55:28.570
the Fed, let's audit
our intellects.

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:31.300
Let us audit the ideas
by which we live,

00:55:31.300 --> 00:55:32.640
and see if we can't do better.

00:55:32.640 --> 00:55:36.090
I think at least some
serious investigation

00:55:36.090 --> 00:55:38.640
into the nature of money
and nature of credit

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:41.200
might help us improve our lots.

